cal authors illuminates the goals and characters of ancient philosophizing. These essays reveal a dynamic range of interactions, reactions, tensions, and ambiguities, showing how Greek literary creations impacted and provided the background against which Greek philosophy arose in more intricate and complex ways than previously believed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGreek literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aMythology, Greek. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBrill, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherubin, Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollobert, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesher, J. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Fred D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaddaf, Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaddaff, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeve, C. D. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, P. Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWians, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWians, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWoodruff, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://